==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*sef-''.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[sevo]], Old Norse [[sefi]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'seva/

===Noun===
'''sefa''' ''m''
# [[spirit]], [[mind]]
#:''Ealle þa gemoniað modes fusne sefan to siþe'': all these things urge he who is eager of spirit to travel.  (''The Seafarer'')

